				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\mathrm{T}}_{\mathrm{sum}}={\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{m_f}}{t}_i^2 $$\end{document}Tsum=∑i=1mfti2

Phenotypes were simulated using the following linear model: y = g1 + g2 + e, where g1 ~ N(0, G1 * σg12), g2 ~ N(0, G2 * σg22), and e ~ N(0, I * σe2). G1 and G2 are the genomic relationship matrices for causal SNPs in C1 and C2, respectively. The total phenotypic variance σP2 = σg12 + σg22 + σe2 was 100 in all scenarios. We simulated data under additive genomic heritabilities \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \left({h}^2=\frac{\sigma_{g1}^2+{\sigma}_{g2}^2}{\sigma_{g1}^2+{\sigma}_{g2}^2+{\sigma}_e^2}\right) $$\end{document}h2=σg12+σg22σg12+σg22+σe2 of 0.1, 0.2, or 0.3, to analyse scenarios with low to intermediate heritabilities, reflecting those observed in the real data. To analyse scenarios with non-uniform SNP effects, the proportion of additive genomic variance explained by the causal SNPs in C1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
